               <msContents>
                  <summary>An abridgment (<hi rend="italic">Intikhāb</hi>) from the <title>ʿArafāt
                        al-ʿĀshiqīn waʿAraṣāt al-ʿĀrifīn</title> (The Plain of ‘Arafāt of the Lovers
                     and Courts of the Gnostics) by <persName role="aut"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/110979716" key="person_110979716">Taqī al-Dīn
                        Awḥadī (d. after 1632-33)</persName>. Originally from Isfahan, the author
                     served the Safavid ruler Shāh ʿAbbās I (b. 1571, r. 1588–1629) then later
                     emigrated to India where he completed his chronicle for a Mughal court official
                     during the reign of the Emperor Jahāngīr (b. 1569, r. 1605–1627). Undated, but
                     probably originally copied in the <date cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian"
                        >18th century</date>, this incomplete manuscript appears repeatedly repaired
                     and augmented by different individuals.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_635-item1">
                     <author ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/110979716" key="person_110979716">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Awḥadī Balyānī, Taqī
                           al-Dīn, 1565-approximately 1640</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">اوحدی بلیانی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7445">Intikhāb-i Taẕkirah-i
                        Awḥadī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7445">انتخاب تذکره اوحدی</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                        انتخاب تذکره اوحدی بلیانی که یکصد هفتاد هزار بیت مکتوبست که در این ایام
                        اتفاق مطالعه آفتاد.</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="58b" to="58b"> برگ ۵۸پ (folio 58b):</locus> آنقیت را چاک دل
                        سوزید باران بعد از این * من ترا قد از وی که دیگر خون نماند. </explicit>
                     <colophon>No colophon.</colophon>
                     <note>The volume opens with verses by <persName role="ctb"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/226077749" key="person_226077749">Abū al-Ḥasan
                           Kharaqānī (967–1033)</persName>, closes with lines by <persName
                           role="ctb" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9223445/" key="person_9223445"
                           >Masīḥ Kāshānī (fl. 17th c.)</persName>, and otherwise frequently
                        references <persName role="ctb" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/65143027/"
                           key="person_65143027">Sirāj al-Dīn ʻAlī Khān Ārzū (ca.
                           1689–1756)</persName> and <persName role="ctb" key="person_50013027"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/50013027/">Ḥazīn Lāhījī (ca.
                           1692–1766)</persName>.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Folios <locus from="9a" to="35b">9 to 35</locus> seem likely
                           original to the volume, comprised of comparatively thin, straight-grained
                           buff-coloured <material>paper</material> with ~8 laid lines per cm,
                           whereas the prior folios <locus from="1a" to="8b">1 to 8</locus> and
                              <locus from="36a" to="57b">36 to 57</locus> of medium-weight,
                           straw-coloured, straight and crossed grained sheets added when restored.
                           Folios <locus from="59a" to="61b">59 to 61</locus> may comprise flyleaves
                           added when restored, probably in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502"
                              >Awadh (Oude)</placeName>. All papers appear likely manufactured in
                           the <placeName cert="high" type="empire"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024418" key="place_7024418"
                              >Mughal Empire</placeName></support>
                        <extent><measure type="folio" quantity="61">61 folios, 2 flyleaves (ff. ii +
                              61 + ii)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>260</height>
                              <width>140</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Foliated in pencilled Arabic numerals when catalogued.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords only appear on folios <locus
                                 from="1b" to="8b">1b to 8b</locus> and <locus from="35a" to="58b"
                                 >35a to 58b</locus>, but may be trimmed off on other
                              folios.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Text in fair condition, with moderate insect damage, discolouration
                              and historical repairs.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="3">
                           <p>Written primarily in written 2 oblique columns (<hi rend="italic"
                                 >chalīpā</hi>) with additional lines written vertically between
                              them, with variant numbers of lines throughout.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="shikastah" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Folios <locus from="9a" to="35b">9a to 35b</locus>, probably original,
                           appear written in a dense, hasty <material>black</material> shikastah,
                           with names of poets, verse headers and markers in
                              <material>red</material>.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="shikastah" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Folios <locus from="1b" to="8b">1b to 8b</locus> and <locus from="35a"
                              to="58b">35a to 58b</locus> written in a comparatively clear
                              <material>black</material> shikastah hand with names of poets, verse
                           headers and markers in <material>red</material>..</desc>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nasta_liq shikastah" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Folios <locus from="59a" to="61b">59a to 61b</locus> feature a mix of
                           other <material>black</material> shikastah and nasta‘liq hand(s).</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Marginal notes and poems throughout in several
                     hands. <lb/>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item> The <locus from="1a" to="1a">first right flyleaf a side (f.
                              1a)</locus> bears the title of the work, likely in the hand of
                              <persName role="wst" cert="high" key="person_f6587">Muhīn
                              Dās</persName>, and assistant to former owner <persName
                              key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                              William Hamilton</persName>. </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears two notes dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1822-05-22" to="1822-06-19">Ramaz̤ān
                              1237 (May–June 1822)</date> and <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              when="1846-03-02">4 Rabīʿ I 1262 (2 March 1846)</date>.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left doublure</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with shelfmark <q xml:lang="en"
                        >1/E</q>, <q xml:lang="en">Hamilton MSS No. 552</q>. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1858" notAfter="1863">
                        <p> Rebound in a British-Indian hydrid style, probably in <placeName
                              type="city" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481"
                              >Multan</placeName>, for former owner <persName role="fmo pat"
                              key="person_f830" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William
                              Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Sewing undetermined due to tight opening. Edges trimmed and with twined
                           chevron endbands in green and red <material>silk</material> worked over
                           round cores at head and tail. Covered in full, tight backed, red goatskin
                              <material>leather</material>, with squares at the edges and defined
                           joints, but without a flap (type III binding per Déroche). Internal
                           doublures of the same <material>leather</material>, with the excess width
                           adhered as hinges on the the first and last flyleaves, then covered with
                           strips of paper to disguise the joins.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>264</height>
                              <width>154</width>
                              <depth>16</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Binding in good condition, with some external
                           abrasion</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>
                        <p>Three <material>vermilion</material> library seal impressions of the
                           kings of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502"
                              key="place_7001502">Awadh (Oude)</placeName>, intaglio-carved in
                           nasta‘līq script in two stacked lines on folios <locus from="2a" to="2a"
                              >2a</locus> and <locus from="61b" to="61b">61b</locus>, with another
                           small <material>black</material>rectangular seal.</p></summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>1:</label> Rectangular seal of the library of <persName
                              role="fmo seal" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"
                              key="person_265857376">Nāṣir al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803, r.
                              1827–1837)</persName>, within two stacked cartouches, double-ruled and
                           dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828" notAfter="1829"
                              >1244 AH (1828–1829 CE)</date>, inscribed with his title <addName
                              type="epithet" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"
                              key="person_265857376">Sulaymān Jāh</addName>::<lb/><q xml:lang="fa">
                              خوش است مهر کتبخانه سلیمان جاه * بهر کتاب مزین چو نقش بسم الله،
                              ١٢۴۴</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="italic">Khvush ast muhur-i kitābkhānah-'i
                                 Sulaymān Jāh bahr-i kitāb; muzayyin chaw naqsh-i basmallah</hi>,
                                 <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 </date></q> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal
                              of the library of Sulaymān Jāh is good; it embellishes the book like
                              the design of a <hi rend="italic">basmallah</hi>, <date
                                 calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1828-07-14"
                                 notAfter="1829-07-02">1244 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>17</height>
                              <width>37</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>

                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Rectangular library seal, surmounted by the royal
                           emblem of Awadh, of <persName role=" seal fmo"
                              key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                              ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006/">Amjad ‘Alī Shāh
                              (b. 1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, with beaded ruling and dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09"
                              >1260 AH (1844–1845 CE)</date>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">ناسخ هر مهر شد چون شد مزین بر کتاب * خاتم امجد علی شاه
                              زمان عالیجناب، ١٢٦٠</q><lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Nāsukh har muhur shud chun
                                 shud muzayyin bar kitāb; khātim-i Amjad ‘Alī Shāh zamān-i
                                 ‘Ālījanāb</hi>, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                 notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1260</date></q> (<q
                              xml:lang="en">Every [prior] seal became cancelled since the book
                              became embellished by the seal of Amjad ‘Alī Shāh in the era of his
                              Sublime Majesty, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1844-01-22"
                                 notAfter="1845-01-09">1260 AH</date></q>).<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>53</height>
                              <width>45</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal>
                        <p><label>3:</label> Rectangular seal surmounted by the royal emblem Awadh,
                           of <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role="fmo"
                              key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (1822–1887), King of Awadh (r.
                              1847–1856)</persName> dated <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                              notBefore="1846" notAfter="1847">1262 AH (1846–47 CE)</date>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><quote xml:lang="fa"> خاتم
                                 واجد علی سلطان عالم بر کتاب * ثابت و پر نور بادا تا فروغ آفتاب،
                                 ١٢۶۲ </quote></p>
                           <p><quote xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"><hi rend="italic">Khātim-i Wājid ‘Alī,
                                    Sulṭān-i ‘Ālam bar kitāb, s̄abit va pur nūr bādā tā farūgh-i
                                    āftāb</hi>, 1262</quote> (<q xml:lang="en">The seal of Wājid
                                 ‘Alī, Sulṭān of the World, upon the book shall be permanent and as
                                 bright as sunlight, <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                                    notBefore="1844-01-22" notAfter="1845-01-09">1262 AH [1847
                                    CE]</date></q>.</p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>41</height>
                                 <width>26</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>4:</label> folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a
                           rectangular seal impression, intaglio carved in nasta‘līq script, in two
                           stacked lines, single-ruled, with the name of a former associate that
                           possibly reads <persName cert="medium" role="fmo asn seal"
                              key="person_f6940">Nīnkā Bayg Khān</persName> dated <date
                              calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1814-12-14" to="1815-12-02">1230 AH
                              (1814–15 CE)</date>:</p>
                        <decoNote type="stamp" subtype="inscription"><p><q xml:lang="fa"> نینکا بیگ
                                 خان بندهٔ حسین، ١٢۳۰ </q></p>
                           <p><dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                                 <height>13</height>
                                 <width>14</width>
                              </dimensions></p></decoNote>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin> Possibly completed in the <origPlace cert="medium" type="empire"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024418" key="place_7024418">Mughal
                        Empire</origPlace>; undated, but possibly <date cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian">18th century</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Previously held in the royal library of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001502" key="place_7001502">Awadh
                           (Oude)</placeName> in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001561" key="place_7001561"
                           >Lucknow</placeName>, as indicated by library seal impressions on folio
                           <locus from="155b" to="155b">155b</locus> of the Kings of Awadh <persName
                           type="person" role="fmo" key="person_265857376"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/265857376"> Nāṣir al-Dīn Ḥaydar Shāh (b. 1803,
                           r. 1827–1837)</persName>, <persName role="fmo"
                           key="person_9680150325559110090006"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/9680150325559110090006"> Amjad ‘Alī Shāh (b.
                           1801, r. 1842–1847)</persName>, and <persName type="person"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/305855167" role="fmo seal"
                           key="person_305855167">Wājid ‘Alī Shāh (b. 1822, r.
                        1847–1856)</persName>, then presumably looted during India's First War of
                        Independence, when British soldiers ransacked the Kaisabagh palace and
                        library on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1858-03-15">15 March
                           1858</date> (see Wolseley's Memoir).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName type="supplied"
                           key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George
                           William Hamilton (1807-1868)</persName> who served in <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                           >India</placeName>
                        <date from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>, latterly as
                        Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535"
                           >Delhi</placeName>. He acquired over a thousand Indian and Persian
                        manuscripts, from which the <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                           >British Museum</orgName> purchased 352 from his widow, <persName
                           key="person_f8470" role="fmo">Charlotte Logie Hamilton
                           (1817–1893)</persName>, now held in the <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>
                        <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058"> Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder of Hamilton's collection
                        in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1868">1868</date> for his <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                        >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                        Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
